---
import Base from "@layouts/Base.astro";
import { loadRatesData } from "@lib/rates";
import { formatUpdatedAt } from "@lib/format";

const data = await loadRatesData();
---

<Base
  title="Methodology"
  description="How we collect and calculate the rates shown on Canadian Rates."
  canonical="https://canadianrates.ca/methodology"
>
  <h1>Methodology</h1>
  <p>Last updated {formatUpdatedAt(data.updated_at)}.</p>

  <h2>Where the posted rates come from</h2>
  <p>
    For each lender we display, we automatically read the rates published on
    that lender's public mortgage rates page. For lenders whose sites cannot
    be read by an automated scraper, we maintain the rates manually based on
    their published rate sheets. We always link to the source page on each
    lender's profile so you can verify.
  </p>

  <h2>Where the discounted rates come from</h2>
  <p>
    Most major Canadian banks publish two rates on their public mortgage
    pages: a "posted" rate and a special-offer rate (sometimes labelled
    "special rate," "limited-time offer," or "promotional rate"). The
    discounted rate shown on this site is the bank's own published
    special-offer rate, captured directly from the same source page as the
    posted rate. We do not estimate, derive, or apply a haircut.
  </p>
  <p>
    When a lender publishes only one rate (for example, Tangerine), the
    posted and discounted columns show the same value. When a lender does
    not publish a special-offer rate for a given term, that row shows the
    posted rate only.
  </p>
  <p>
    A mortgage broker can typically secure a rate below the bank's
    published special-offer rate. The actual rate you qualify for depends
    on your credit score, down payment, property type, and the broker's
    relationship with the lender. Always confirm directly with a lender or
    broker.
  </p>

  <h2>How often rates update</h2>
  <p>
    The site rebuilds daily. Each lender's profile shows when their rates were
    last successfully scraped.
  </p>

  <h2>How the rate trend chart works</h2>
  <p>
    Each successful scraper run also writes a single-day aggregate to a rate-
    history file: the lowest discounted rate across tracked lenders for each
    term, plus the average across the lenders that offered that term, plus a
    count. The chart on the home page and the term pages plots the daily
    "best discounted" line.
  </p>
  <p>
    We only show data we actually collected — there is no synthesised
    history. The first daily snapshot is dated {formatUpdatedAt(data.updated_at)};
    earlier days are not represented because we did not track them. The
    chart's empty-state message appears until at least two distinct days
    of snapshots have accumulated.
  </p>

  <h2>How we write our guides</h2>
  <p>
    Each guide is researched against primary sources (the Bank of Canada, OSFI,
    CMHC, lender rate sheets, and federal mortgage regulations), then drafted,
    edited for clarity, and reviewed before publication. The math behind every
    interactive tool is implemented as pure functions with unit tests, so the
    same calculation runs in the browser and in our test suite.
  </p>
  <p>
    We commit to reviewing each guide every quarter and updating it whenever
    underlying rules change (for example, a CMHC premium tier change or a
    federal stress-test rule update). Every guide has a "Last reviewed" date
    visible at the top of the page.
  </p>
</Base>
